From 1b048fc3d029c293800464b0ce0409a50ef34da1 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Entrpi <entrpi@proton.me>
Date: Sat, 7 Feb 2026 22:50:25 +1100
Subject: [PATCH 088/118] Bluetooth: btrtl: Fix NULL pointer dereference on USB
 disconnect
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

btrtl_initialize uses separate 'ret' and 'rc' variables for error
returns.  The btrtl_vendor_read_reg16(RTL_SEC_PROJ) call at the end
stores its result in 'rc', but on failure jumps to err_free which
returns ERR_PTR(ret).  If a preceding operation (e.g. rtl_read_rom_version)
succeeded, ret is still 0, so ERR_PTR(0) = NULL is returned.

The caller btrtl_setup_realtek checks IS_ERR(btrtl_dev) which is false
for NULL, then passes NULL to btrtl_download_firmware causing a NULL
pointer dereference in the kernel.

This occurs in practice when a USB Bluetooth adapter disconnects
during initialization (e.g. due to PHY or controller issues) — the
RTL_SEC_PROJ vendor read fails with -ENODEV but ret holds 0 from the
successful rom_version read.

Fix by using 'ret' consistently instead of 'rc', and remove the now
unused 'rc' variable.

diff --git a/drivers/bluetooth/btrtl.c b/drivers/bluetooth/btrtl.c
index 5603b282f9bc1..7c03c7888b9a2 100644
--- a/drivers/bluetooth/btrtl.c
+++ b/drivers/bluetooth/btrtl.c
@@ -1073,7 +1073,6 @@ struct btrtl_device_info *btrtl_initialize(struct hci_dev *hdev,
 	u16 hci_rev, lmp_subver;
 	u8 hci_ver, lmp_ver, chip_type = 0;
 	int ret;
-	int rc;
 	u8 key_id;
 	u8 reg_val[2];
 
@@ -1185,8 +1184,8 @@ struct btrtl_device_info *btrtl_initialize(struct hci_dev *hdev,
 		goto err_free;
 	}
 
-	rc = btrtl_vendor_read_reg16(hdev, RTL_SEC_PROJ, reg_val);
-	if (rc < 0)
+	ret = btrtl_vendor_read_reg16(hdev, RTL_SEC_PROJ, reg_val);
+	if (ret < 0)
 		goto err_free;
 
 	key_id = reg_val[0];
-- 
